For the Governor

-----Original Message-----
From: Greg Norell [mailto:gnorell@norellinc.com] 
Sent: Thursday, July 30, 2009 6:10 PM
To: Office of the Governor
Subject: Our brief introduction on July 29th

Governor Perdue,


Please allow me to introduce myself. My Name is Greg Norell. Together  
with my wife, Terry and 4 children, we reside at 1377 Old Dry Creek  
Road, Morganton, NC 28655.

Terry and I met with you briefly yesterday afternoon while we were  
walking through the Capitol, absorbing North Carolina History,  
admiring the documents written by John Adams.

We knew you were busy when you asked us if we resided in the state, so  
I kept my response short and indicated we were from Western North  
Carolina. Please excuse my ignorance, I had no intention of being  
hasteful. We actually had a lot on our minds that we wanted to convey  
to you about our experience over the past year.

It was just over a year ago that Terry and I made one of the most  
controversial decisions in our lives and that was to pick up our  
family of six from the state of New Jersey, where we both lived for  
the past forty years. I know that you must be thinking...moving out of  
NJ could not be so difficult. We left behind, family and friends to  
chart a new course in life not only for us, but more importantly for  
our four young children.

We not only discovered North Carolina, but we discovered the people  
and geographic beauty of the foothills of the Blue Ridge Mountains at  
Lake James in Western North Carolina.

We simply wanted to convey to you Governor Perdue, that we are pleased  
to be permanent residents of the state of North Carolina. While it was  
a very difficult to head into uncharted territory, personally,  
professionally and geographically, not realizing the economic storm  
that was in front of us nine months ago, we believe it was a  
monumental decision of a lifetime, perhaps precisely because of the  
struggle to make the right decision.

Our trip to Raleigh was by no means random. It was our second trip to  
the capital in as many months. We were there yesterday a bit early,  
anticipating traffic problems due to the visit of President Obama on  
our way to a meeting at 6pm for the final disposition by the Joint  
Commission for Municipal Incorporation, regarding the Village of Lake  
James.

We had some time on our hands and we thought we might stop by the  
museums to learn a little more about the state. The capitol caught our  
eye and we proceeded to go on the self guided tour.

Unfortunately, the Commission did not give a favorable review of the  
application sponsored by Senator Jim Jacumin, when in fact all of the  
legal criteria was met for each and every phase. Various members of  
the commission questioned the issue of contiguity, when in fact the  
Commission asked and was advised by David M. Lawrence, the leading  
authority in NC on this and many other issues involving municipal  
incorporations, that in fact the area meets the requirements of  
contiguity.

Certainly, the entire issue is charged with great emotion and I fully  
understand that there is indeed a political process that must occur.  
While I am not currently directly involved with the task force for the  
formation of the Village of Lake James, I can tell you without bias,  
meeting multiple times with the proponents of the Village that these  
individuals not only care deeply for the entire diverse community, but  
also have the foresight to understand that the only constant is change  
itself.

You made a very strong impression on both of us when you spoke at the  
grand opening ceremony of the North Carolina Research Campus in  
Kannapolis last October on how government, industry and private  
individuals can come together to achieve great accomplishments. We  
were amazed, astonished and inspired at what was accomplished in such  
a short period of time. The vision of David Murdock was brought to  
fruition, not because it was easy, but because of the realization that  
it was the right thing to do for the long term in spite of the  
daunting and seemingly insurmountable task of getting the project off  
the ground.

This is a small local issue compared to the NCRC. However, Terry and  
I  sincerely believe that there are many great minds in the group of  
proponents for the formation of the Village of Lake James that will  
act in a similar fashion as Mr. Murdock to secure the future of this  
region for the next one hundred years through education, technology  
and retirement  while preserving the natural beauty of this  
magnificent landscape.

I understand that there is a fair amount of resistance to passing this  
bill through the current session and that the chances are very slim  
that it would even make it out of the Senate as I write this.

Before yesterday afternoon we had no intention of petitioning anyone  
for help, much less the Governor of the state of North Carolina but I  
developed a compelling need to contact you after our brief hello and  
making the connection to the NCRC.

Lake James is our final destination. It is home to our family. I  
believe the NCRC will be home to a part of our business someday soon  
as well. The region is full of unlimited potential for the  
technological future only if we plan with unrelenting fervor not  
tomorrow, but today.

Please feel to contact me with any questions, comments or concerns at  
any time by phone or email. Home Tel: 828.584.6092, Mobile: 828.448.1494


Yours, Sincerely,


